   @subsection (label=subsec:rendering) Rendering and Graphics Drivers\

   As mentioned before, display refreshes are triggered only when needed. The GraphicsManager calls the current screen's render function, which iterates throught two on-screen components and invokes their render methods.
   After that, the manager iterates throught installed graphics drivers and sends those returned strings for rendering.

   @code (language=rust, label=lst:graphics-driver) codes/graphics/driver.txt\

   When developing this graphics library, I opted for an almost completely abstract approach, so that future changes or updates will result easy and effortless.

   @newpage\

   @section (label=sec:settings) Settings and Configurations\

   As I mentioned earlier, one of my main goals when structuring this project was abstraction. Because I want to keep updating and expanding this project over the next few years, I couldn't just hardcode configurations or dump everything into a single file. I needed a system where parts of the code could be seamlessly swapped or upgraded without breaking the rest of the software.
   \\
   To achieve this, I built a **component-based configuration engine** from scratch. It uses the ESP-IDF virtual filesystem (VFS) to talk to a dedicated flash memory partition formatted with **LittleFS** (which is perfect for embedded microcontrollers because it handles sudden power cuts safely).
   \\
   The core of this system is the SettingsManager, which acts as a central coordinator for different modules like graphics, MIDI mappings, or pad sensitivities.
   \\
   Storing different kinds of configuration modules in a single place is a classic programming challenge. A "MIDI Component" needs completely different variables than a "Graphics Component," but the central manager needs to treat them all uniformly.
   \\
   In C++, this can be solved with unsafe pointer casting @latex {(void*),} but coming to Rust forced me to think differently. I implemented a thread-safe, polymorphic architecture using a HashMap wrapped inside a Mutex:

   @code (language=rust, label=lst:settings-components) codes/settings/components.txt\

   By using a dynamic trait object (Box), the manager can store any module that implements my SettingsComponent trait.
   \\
   When a specific part of the system needs to read its parameters, it retrieves the component and uses runtime downcasting via Rust's std::any::Any trait to safely recover the original, concrete layout:

   @code (language=rust, label=lst:settings-polymorphism) codes/settings/polymorphism.txt\

   What I love about this pattern is that the main manager doesn't need to know what data is inside each component. It just acts as a storage locker, keeping the code beautifully decoupled.
   \\
   For saving data permanently onto the ESP32's flash memory, I used the Serde framework to handle serialization, storing everything in human-readable TOML files.
   Since manual file editing or software updates can sometimes introduce bugs or corrupt files, I knew I needed a fallback mechanism. I wrote a helper function utilizing Rust's Default trait to ensure the device never crashes (panics) due to a missing or corrupted file at boot:

   @code (language=rust, label=lst:settings-serde.txt) codes/settings/serde.txt\

   If a configuration file is missing, the system catches the error, generates a clean set of defaults, writes it back to the storage partition, and keeps running smoothly.
   \\
   Finally, to handle communication between different parts of the system without running into the strict memory access rules enforced by Rust's borrow checker, I integrated a *std::sync::mpsc* channel.
   \\
   When a new component is attached via @latex {\textit{add\_component},} it receives a cloned transmitter (Sender). This allows isolated background tasks to safely send real-time configuration updates back to the main control thread asynchronously, keeping the entire application organized and responsive.

   @code (language=rust, label=lst:settings-add-component) codes/settings/add-component.txt\

   SettingsManager's interior mutability allows the structure to be wrapped into a *std::sync::Arc* and to be securely passed to multiple threads.
}